The screws are unscrewed. Remove the shell. WARNING: the metal shield inside may still be hot! Step 1: Disassembly Unscrew the screws of the device, remove both the outter shell and the heatsync inside.
The heatsync is hold in place with little notches, just pull them back. (Sorry for the weird angles of the images) The metal piece is the heatsync. This is the device with the heatsync removed. See the black button to the left? This one is too short, while the white button has an extension, so you can press it without using something thin. We are going to add the extension to the black button. Meanwhile the black thing to the left is the extension. Put it into the part shown in the image below. This is the shield that has the hole for the reset button. Just stick the extension into the hole that says Step 2: Assembly Now put everything back together in order. Make sure the heatsync is on correctly, and nothing is loose. Finished! We now have a little reset button that we can press without using a thin stick or similar. Remember, this can be used on other things where the reset button is hard to reach. You will most likely need some resizing though. Thanks for reading!

UPDATE: There is a new version of this design which is more reliable to print and easier to assemble. I highly recommend you use it instead: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:243278

At last, here is the much-requested 100% printable heart gears. No more ugly bolt holes! This was designed along the same lines as the screwless cube gears: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10483, and in fact uses the exact same center block (though the pins are slightly shorter). UPDATE: If you lack a 3D printer, you can now buy these from CarryTheWhat at http://www.etsy.com/shop/CarryTheWhat. The size has been increased a bit from the previous version to accommodate the printed pins, so it now measures 100mm across when assembled. Since everything is now printable, it should be easy to scale this design up or down as you see fit. At this size it took me ~6 hours of printing time on my TOM.

Print the parts list.  The separate files for gears 1, 3, 5, and 7 are just there in case you have a problem with the four gear plate, or if you want them in separate colors.  Use multiply to print four of the pin pairs at once.
Plug the short pins into the holes on the small faces of the center block; plug the long pins into the large faces.  Slide each gear onto its corresponding pin.  I like to start at the top, because it's more obvious how the gears align with each other when you work your way down.  
It's always difficult to calibrate a printer to make perfectly fitting bushings, but the good news is if your heart comes out too tight to turn nicely or so loose it's wobbly, all you have to do is make new pins.  You can either regenerate them with different parameters from the scad file, or you can just take the existing pin file and stretch it as required in the various axes.  This means the big prints won't be ruined by a miscalibration.

Ever wanted to collect every last bobblehead in real life? Well now you can!
Scale, print, paint, and display your very own custom bobblehead collection exported straight from the Fallout 4 game meshes. These files have been prepped for printing in Netfabb and posted for you to enjoy.
I've updated the files so that you can optionally print the body and head separately for each model. Drill the holes, add a spring from a click-pen, and you've got a functional bobblehead! This will also help with overhangs. Intelligence and Science wear glasses and Luck has a top hat, so there are three different head shapes. Agility's head is fused to his body due to the angle of his body and the turn of his head.

Printer:

ORDbot Hadron

Rafts:

No

Yes

Resolution:

0.3mm for 4.6x scaled print

40%

Notes: Some things to consider before you begin this project:
  • The files are about 16mm tall by default. This is the size that they came in when exported from the game. I have not scaled them in any way.
  • Most of the heads are lightly attached at the neck. (Agility is fully joined to the body) This leaves the possibility for you to "break" the head off and install your own spring or balance pin to but some bobble into your creations!
  • I used a scale of 4.6 to get a Charisma bobblehead that is exactly 75mm tall. 6.2x scale to get a 100mm tall bobblehead.
    • Your final ABS prints will greatly benefit from an acetone bath to smooth the surfaces. That's what I intend to do eventually. Luck's 4-leaf clover is so thin that it will be impossible to print. I have included a file that omits the clover so that you can add your own later. A greed twist-tie and some paper petals should work great!

• Installed programs Bethesda Archive Extractor and NifSkope.
  • Extracted the bobblehead .nif files with BAE.
  • Imported .nif files into NifSkope and exported .obj files.
  • Converted .obj files to .stl files using an online converter.
  • Repaired each new .stl using the Netfabb Cloud tool.

title: Throttle valve for the Toyota throttle body

description.text:
While waiting for the hardware needed for the assembly of the awesome Toyota model engine designed by ericthepoolboy I did a throttle valve for the throttle body.
When putting the engine together I thought I would incorparate a speed control for the electric motor.
Either the one suggested by rubb3rtoe http://www.thingiverse.com/make:128131 or something similar.
If so it would be cool to incorperate the potentiometer as a Throttle Positioning Sensor on the throttle body so the throttle could be used to rev the engine. Either directly on the intake or via some wire.
Or the other way around, to put a stepper motor that controls the valve in correlation to the selected speed. Anyway, will see if I get that far. For now it is only the valve which can be fixed on a bolt or rod going through the throttle body and the throttle linkage.
I used a M3x45mm screw which I filed flat on one side. The valve is secured by two M2x1.5mm screws.
You can choose to print the valve as it is. (The file called Throttle_valve.stl)
If so I recommend to print with supports.
Or you can print the two split files and glue them together.
I tried both and it is mostly a matter if you prefer to clean away support structure or to mess with glue. For those who have not yet installed their throttle body to the inlet I used three M3x15mm and one M3x12mm screws. Will change them to allen screws later on though.

description.text: Please watch this video for more information and to see them in action: https://youtu.be/2W8YSOQ2y48 I had this idea a few days ago and thought they'd be fun to make. These were printed using black PLA and clear PLA (http://www.amazon.com/HATCHBOX-Transparent-3D-Printer-Filament/dp/B00M0CS8N2/ref=sr_1_1). description.text:
The Y axis on my HYREL seemed kind of loose and there's no way to tension it so I made one! 
This will only work if you have one of their newer versions where they use this slotted aluminum as the Y-axis arm. You may have to make your own if your dimensions aren't quite the same, but it is very simple. 
It needs two 10-12mm m3 bolts to secure it to the arm and one 15-20mm m3 bolt to hold a 3x4x10mm roller bearing. Three nuts (one for each bolt) and 10-15 washers to space things right.
Attach the bearing as shown (5 washer between the bearing and the printed part), slide two nuts into the arm a few inches, lightly screw the bottom two bolts in with the bearing inside the belt and slide the bearing towards the idler to put tension on the belt. Don't overdo it, but this should help make your parts more accurate!
Now on to the X axis :)

title: Light Tight Enclosure for Microscope Sample V.1

description.text:
This is a light tight sample enclosure that I designed and 3D printed for keeping background light out from coupling into a microscope. The design is just a box. It took me longer to get the data here that shows how well it works than it did to design it. 
Knocking out background room light is particularly a problem with non descanned laser scanning light microscopy systems. You can see how well this simple enclosure worked at shielding the detectors from background room light coupling through the microscope objective in the included images. 
The microscope this is sitting on is a Olympus IX71. 
The nice part about 3D printing the box vs. making it from hand is that it is easily made light tight.This box is small enough to on a 200mmx200mm bed.
I printed it in black ABS.

An scad model of the cheap ultrasonic sensor/range finder from ebay. Part number HC-SR04.  
This is intended to help model a maze mouse that uses these sensors. The model is based on limited information (basic dimensions) and a photo. Hopefully it is about right.  
Updated the model with better dimensions from a more comprehensive datasheet. Should be correct now.

comments.text: Nice looking model. I just bought a "Sainsmart" HC-SR04 module from Amazon, and it has slightly different dimensions than this model. The two transducers are on 1.00 inch (25.4 mm) centers, it has four corner holes instead of two, and they are a bit smaller (1.5mm in diameter).  So just beware, if you need an accurate model to download, check your particular sensor before assuming dimensions on this one matches yours.
